{"/service/ndnp/az/batch_az_bentonite_ver02/data/sn95060771/00517019227/1924030801/1218.xml":{"full_text":"CONDITION OF THE ARIZONA\nCOPPER MINING INDUSTRY\nBy DR. L. D. RICKETTS\nPresident Inspiration Consolidated\nCopper Company\nDirector New Cornelia Copper Co.\nThe three chief producing in\ndustries of Arizona are copper min\ning, agriculture and live stock. A\nfourth industry, transportation, is\nessential to them and to the inter\nests of the state generally. It is\nvery evident that the welfare of these\nindustries and the prosperity of the\nentire state are inseparable because\nthe degree of prosperity of these\nfour industries measures the\namount of employment for the work\nmen and the amount of general\nbusiness for the merchant and the\nprofessional man. If one industry\nsuffers, we must all suffer.\nThe recent panic is too fresh in\nour minds to be forgotten. I well\nremember the huge stack of unsal\nable copper, over 30,000 tons of it,\npiled in the yard of one of our\nsmelters. We all remember the\nacres of unsalable bales of cotton\nabout the railway sidings. And I\nhope we all remember the courage\nof our substantial business houses\nWe Handle All Necessary\nGOLF SUPPLIES\nEverything needed on the new Ajo course.\nThey are not expensive. Call and see them\nand get our prices.\nINFORMATION BUREAU\nAsk us any question in regard to Golf and\nthe Ajo Golf Club. Membership Cards may\nbe secured here.\nAJO DRUG CO.\nFRITZ SCHROEDER, PROP.\nNew Cornelia Copper Co.\nAjo. Arizona\nI\nGORDON R. CAMPBELL President\nTHOMAS HOATSON 3 T First Vice-President\nEDWIN J. COLLINS Second Vice-President\nJAMES E. FISHER Secretary and Treasurer\nAUGUSTUS J. DUNSTAN Assist. Sec. and Treas.\nH. B. PAULL Auditor\nJOHN C. GREENWAY General Manager\nM. CURLEY General Superintendent\nW. L. DuMOULIN *J Assist. General Superintendent\nW. F. NASH Chief Clerk\nAJO COPPER NEWS\nand banks throughout the country\nwhich stood together and carried\nthe producer until he could at last\nfind a buyer for his product, if\neven at a low price.\nAgriculture and Cattle, Improved\nThe agricultural industry has\npassed its crisis. The year 1923\nmarks a return to prosperity and\nthe outlook for the future seems\nbright.\nThe live stock industry is now\nbeginning to improve and the out\nlook for its prosperity is good.\nThe railways have fq'rtun^telw\nescaped from the evil of Federal\nmanagement and at rates below the\nwar level are doing fairly well,\nthough none too well.\nCopper Only Disturbing Feature\nThe only disturbing feature is\nthe condition of the copper min\ning industry. The cost of reduc\ning copper has increased immensely\nsince war times and for many of\nour mines there is no profit when\ncopper sells at thirteen cents.\nBusiness conditions in the United\nStates are basically sound. The\ncountry is prosperous and growing\nI and its people are at yvork. Never\nin the history of this country has\nthe consumption of copper been as\ngreat as it is now. Last year the\nconsumption was double of that of\n1923. We are now consuming in\nthis country nearly as much cop\nper as we produce in spite of our\nrecord production. Thus in 1923\nwe only produced about five per\ncent, more copper than w r e consumed\nwhere formerly it was forty per\ncent.\nCauses of Low Selling Price\nWhat then are the causes of the\nlow selling price? I see three\ncauses:\nThe first is that the African\nCongo and the West Coast of South\nAmerica have mines of surpassing\nsize and richness worked with\nvery cheap labor, which we do not\nwish and will not tolerate. South\nAmerica has wages about one\nthird of ours, cheaper freight rates,\nand richer ore. These two regions\nare now producing some four\nhundred thousands tons of copper\nannually and promise to produce\nmore at a cost that even our best\nmines cannot compete with.\nThe second and chief cause is\nthat Europe is not at peace, has not\nsettled down to peaceful pursuits\nand its present consumption of cop\nper\u2014no greater than it was in 1913\n\u2014is not sufficient to consume this\nincrease from Africa and South\nAmerica.\nThe third cause is the action the\nfederal and state governments have\ntaken in carrying war taxes and war\ntime expenditures into times of\nneace. The effect of this is like\nthat of a slow poison; if pursued\nit will sap the strength of our ex\nisting industries and prevent the\ninitiation of new work.\nThe Four Remedies\nThe remedies are not so plainly\nvisible, but these appeal to me:\nThe first remedy is for us to\nrecognize that we are a part of the\nworld and that the misfortunes\nand suffering of a part must affect\nthe whole, and therefore us. We\nshould therefore do all we can to\ninduce our federal government tc\ngive all the moral support possible\nto European countries .w\u2019hen such\nsupport will tend towards peace\nand peaceful pursuits, and our p:?-\nvate institutions should help Europe\nfinancially when it is safe to do it.\nIf Europe can return to peaceful\npursuits, there is not a doubt that\nits use of copper will double or\ntriple. The high cost of fuel theie\nalone would cause this increase in\ndemand, because it will compel cen\ntralization of power plants and elec\ntrical distribution of power to the\nindustries.\nThe second remedy is to do all\nwe can to stop useless Government\nextravagance and to help lighten\nthe tax burdens placed upon the\nproducing industries of the country\nThese burdens are becoming onerous\nand causing a contraction of in\ndustry that will inevitaably lead\nto unemployment.\nWhile the federal government is\nSave an Hour a Day\nWith a\nfor Economical Trantfortatio*\n2-Pass. Roadster\n*490\nf. o. b. Flint, Mich,\nDAHL GARAGE\n\u2014DEALER\u2014\nHAS. BEAL, ROWOOD\nSTRANGER TRIES TO GET INTO\nPLANT AT MIDNIGHT\nAbout midnight on Wednesday,\nJohn Riley, gatekeeper on duty at\nthe plant, was called to the door\nof his \u201coffice\u201d by a stranger who de\nmanded admittance into the plant.\n\u2018Have you a pass,\u201d asked Riley.\n\u201cNo, I haven\u2019t,\u201d said the stranger.\n\u2018Well, your\u2019r-r-r not a-going to\nget in,\u2019\u201d replied Riley with emphasis\nBut Riley, just emerging from a\nlighted room into the dark, looked\nagain and listened to the voice.\n\u201cWell, w\u2019ell, if it isn\u2019t Jack, my\nboy\u201d\u2014and they clasped hands.\nIt proved to be Jack Riley, ,his\noldest son, who had just arrived\nfrom Coleraine. Minn., on his first\nvisit to Ajo\u2014to his father and\nbrother here. And the son took\ngreat pleasure in thus surprising\nhis father.\nThe visitor says the winter was\nmild up to January, but in that\nmonth it was very cold\u20144 6 below\nzero. He says he has seen it 50\nbelow there. March is a bad month,\nwith freezes and thaws and high\nwinds and other things not in\nevidence in this camp, he says.\nCAPT. MERSHON WRITES BOOK\nIron Ore, the last issue, has the\nfollowing concerning Capt. William\nB. Mershon of Saginaw, Mich., and\nWilliams, Ariz., a director of New\nCornelia and well known in this\ncamp:\n\u201cRecollections of My Fifty Years\nHunting and Fishing,\u201d by \u2018William\nB. Mershon, is an interesting ac\ncount of hunting and fishing ex\nperiences and the wild life in the\ntwo peninsulas of Michigan. It was\npublished last year and has recently\nbeen added to the collections of the\nMarquette County Historical society.\nCapt. Mershon has long been\nknown as an authority on those\nsubjects.\nJohn Ramsay, electrician boss in\nthe concentrator, left for Houston,\nTex., to visit his mother. He will\nbe gone for a short stay.,\nthe major offender in this respect,\nArizona is no laggard, as the farmer\nand miner know. A farmer ad\nvises me his taxes are now six\ndollars an acre; a banker that his\ntaxes have increased five hundred\nper cent, in eight years. The cost\nof copper at a mine I am familiar\nwith is as follows: Labor, forty\none per cent.; supplies ,in which Ari\nzona labor has an interest, forty\nper cent.; miscellaneous, seven per\ncent.; and taxes, twelve per cent.\nI shall not mention the profit be\ncause it is not worth mentioning.\nA third remedy lies in giving the\nproducer of metals and metal pro\nducts the same advantages of co\noperative selling as the law allows\nthe farmer. At present the laws do\nnot permit this, and the present anti\ntrust law should be modified to\npermit it.\nThe Copper and Brass Research\nAssociation has been doing splendid\neduational work in showing the con\nsumer where he can use copper and\nbrass at a saving over other metals\nand substitutes. This is beginning\nto show its effect, and all of us\nshould try and see where it is to\nour advantage to use copper and\nin such cases use it.\nFavors Tariff on Copper\nFinally, if we can succeed as we\nwill in using more copper than we\nproduce, it would be right and fair\nfor our government to give protec\ntion against the importation of chean\ncopper from abroad as it now gives\nprotection to lead, zinc and the\nother metals by establishing an\nlmnor\u2018 duty. T believe this plan\nis being advocated at this time and\nwe should not discourage, but heln\nft along, because later, jf no t now.\nit will prove beneficial.\nT hone you will not consider me\nnessimistic in these remarks. T\nhave had faith in Arizona for a third\nof oontury and that faith was\nnever greater than now. but we mus\nknow and face difficulties and\nwrongs and correct them when\nnecessarv.\n(From Industrie\u2019 Congress Bulle\ntin No. 24. Feb. 23. 1 924. \"Reports\non Arizona Industries).","height":"16875","width":"11451"}}
